Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Mauritius Commercial, Naiade Resorts

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-11T10:51:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-11/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-mauritius-commercial-naiade-resorts.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed to
the highest since at least 1989, adding 0.9 percent to 2,105.62
by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index jumped 1.5
percent to 25,820.42 by 11:10 a.m. in Lagos, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg, heading for the highest close since March
1. Kenya’s All-Share Index tumbled for a third day, erasing 0.5
percent to 75.62 by 1:11 p.m. in Nairobi. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index slipped for a second day, declining
less than 0.1 percent to 1,150.78 as of 10:13 a.m. in Accra.
 Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  was little changed at
862.73 by 11:14 a.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mauritius Commercial Bank (MCB)  , the Indian Ocean island
nation’s largest lender by market value, gained 2 rupees, or 1.1
percent, to 185 rupees, the highest close since Feb. 21, 2008,
before the May 13 deadline for all listed companies to report
earnings for the three months through March 31.  Naiade Resorts
Ltd. (NRL)  , Mauritius’s third-largest leisure operator by
market value, increased 2.5 rupees, or 8.1 percent, to 33.5
rupees, the strongest since February 2010.  Ireland Blyth Ltd. (IBL) 
, the country’s second-largest diversified company,
advanced 4 rupees, or 5.1 percent, to 82 rupees, the highest
close since at least July 1995.  “Stocks are rising today on anticipation of improved
interim earnings announcements from large and mid-cap
companies,” Bhavik Desai, a research analyst at Axys
Stockbroking Ltd., said in a phone interview.  To contact the reporter on this story:
